As the number of my IMDB reviews continues to climb, I enjoy using inferential statistics to compare my individual scores to the IMDB composite (or, the 'People's Opinion'). After 100 reviews and ratings, I found my standard deviation to be around 1.7. Now, I'm not going to provide a lesson here on inferring differences between groups, but I will say that my ratings seems to skew a little high so far (I just started, and I haven't intentionally watched too many bad movies. But, I know the bad movies are out there, and I will eventually get to them, lowering my average movie rating). However, despite skewing high, my scores follow a standard distribution pattern almost identical to that of general society.I give this movie an 8.5 (rounded up to 9 for IMDB). The current IMDB composite score is 6.1 - a difference of +2.4 (rounded to +2.9, and way above the (+ or -) 1.7 threshold for 'normal' in my data set).I know why I like this film. Michelle Williams & Kirsten Dunst are captivating, the soundtrack is awesome, it's an original idea that is ingeniously executed, the casting is amazing, the portrayals of the historical figures were exaggerated just enough to be funny but not enough to be cartoonish, the script is very clever, and the various uses of bright colors were visually appealing.So, what were all of those other reviewers seeing? Did they not understand Watergate? Did the jokes go over their heads? How could people love Michelle Williams and Kursten Dunst in all of those other films, but not love seeing them with 'Dick' (1999)?Perhaps people weren't ready to see a film about Dick in 1999. Maybe it was still too soon after Watergate. Maybe the youth of the 1970's had changed their political views with age. Maybe seeing this film made those former hippies uncomfortable with who they were, or uncomfortable with who they became in their 40's and 50's.I guess political views are sometimes emotional and can't always be expected to follow a rigid statistical pattern. I would like to believe that, with time, society will skew their 6.1 IMDB rating up a little closer to my 8.5, because I think this movie is amazing. Perhaps we all need to process 'Dick' (1999) in our own way, and come to terms with 'Dick' (1999) in our own time. After all, this 90 minutes of 'Dick' (1999) was never intended to make anyone uncomfortable.RealReview Posting Scoring Criteria:
Acting - 1/1;
Casting - 1/1;
Directing - 0.5/1 (prudish directing, occasional terrible framing with extras pulling focus in the scenes);
Story - 1/1;
Writing/Screenplay - 1/1;Total Base Score = 4.5Modifiers (+ or -):
Originality: +1 (I've seen a lot of different takes on Watergate... This is quite unique.);Standout Performances: +1 (Shared between Michelle Williams & Kirsten Dunst.);Ensemble Cast: +1;Music Score/Soundtrack: +1;Quotability: +0.5 (If you watch this movie more than once, you will never stop quoting it.);Directing-Detrimentally Prudish: -0.5 (This is my first use of this modifier. Andrew Fleming really dropped the ball several times in this film. What a waste of great casting...);Total RealReview Rating: 8.5 (rounded up to 9 for IMDB)
